# Testing policy

Every new piece of code — Rust or TypeScript — ships with unit tests in
the same change, not as a follow-up task. A PR (or a Cursor-generated
change) that adds real logic without a test alongside it isn't done.

- Rust: `cargo test --workspace` must pass. Tests live inline in the
  module they test, via `#[cfg(test)] mod tests` — see
  `.cursor/rules/010-rust.mdc`.
- TypeScript: `npm test --workspaces --if-present` (Vitest) must pass.
  Tests are colocated as `<file>.test.ts` next to the file they test —
  see `.cursor/rules/020-typescript.mdc`.
- CI runs both on every push and PR (`.github/workflows/ci.yml`).
  Treat CI passing as the floor, not the goal — a change that adds
  code without a test but happens to not break CI is still incomplete.

Coverage as a percentage isn't the target; behavior coverage is. A
test should fail if the behavior it documents breaks — not just
execute a line for the sake of a coverage number. Prefer a few sharp
tests that pin down real behavior (including edge cases) over many
shallow ones that only exercise the happy path.
